# verifiably-go environment — copy to `.env` and edit for your deployment.
#
# deploy.sh sources this file at startup and passes it to every `docker
# compose` invocation via --env-file, so the same file drives both the
# verifiably-go container + every DPG service and the browser-facing URLs
# in backends.json / auth-providers.json.
#
# The ONE variable that actually needs to change between laptop and EC2
# is VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_HOST. Everything else has a sane default.

# =============================================================================
# 1. Browser-visible host for every service the user reaches in a browser
# =============================================================================
#
# This is the single knob to flip for a new deployment target.
#
#   Docker Desktop (Windows / Mac) — default:
#       VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_HOST=localhost
#     Published ports are accessible at localhost from the host browser.
#     172.24.0.1 (the bridge gateway) is inside Docker Desktop's VM and
#     is NOT reachable from the host browser — always use localhost here.
#
#   Linux host with native Docker:
#       VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_HOST=172.24.0.1
#     The waltid_default bridge gateway is routable from the Linux host.
#     localhost also works (ports are published on 0.0.0.0).
#
#   EC2 / remote host:
#       VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_HOST=ec2-1-2-3-4.compute-1.amazonaws.com
#     Browser reaches published ports on the EC2 public hostname.
VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_HOST=localhost

# PUBLIC_HOST is the name the shared docker-compose.yml + seed scripts use.
# Kept as an alias so one variable drives both halves.
PUBLIC_HOST=${VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_HOST}

# -------- Per-service subdomains (one-knob switch) --------------------------
#
# When set, every service URL is derived as printf "$VERIFIABLY_HOSTS_PATTERN"
# "<slug>" instead of the legacy "$VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_HOST:$PORT" form. Use
# this when you have per-service A records (e.g. walt-issuer.example.com,
# wso2.example.com, ...) pointed at the same VPS and a TLS-terminating
# reverse proxy (Caddy, nginx, Traefik) routing by Host header.
#
# Slugs used by deploy.sh:
#   wso2, keycloak, walt-issuer, walt-wallet, walt-verifier,
#   inji-certify, inji-certify-preauth, inji-verify, inji-verify-ui,
#   inji-web, esignet, mimoto, verifiably
#
# Empty (the default) keeps the legacy localhost-port behaviour. Verifiably-go
# itself stays backend-agnostic — same binary, both modes — because the URL
# choice happens at deploy-time when backends.json + auth-providers.json are
# generated.
#
# Example:
#   VERIFIABLY_HOSTS_PATTERN=https://%s.example.com
VERIFIABLY_HOSTS_PATTERN=

# When VERIFIABLY_HOSTS_PATTERN is set, deploy.sh brings up the
# `caddy-public` service which TLS-terminates each subdomain and routes
# by Host header. It needs two more vars:
#   VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_DOMAIN — bare apex (must match the domain in the
#                              pattern above; "example.com" if pattern is
#                              "https://%s.example.com")
#   VERIFIABLY_LE_EMAIL      — Let's Encrypt account email. Without it
#                              Caddy uses an internal CA — fine for local
#                              dev with /etc/hosts overrides, NOT for a
#                              public deploy where browsers reject the cert.
VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_DOMAIN=
VERIFIABLY_LE_EMAIL=

# Per-service slug overrides for the public Caddyfile + verifiably-go's
# generated URLs. Empty value = "skip this service" (no Caddy block,
# falls back to host:port for verifiably-go). Default is the canonical
# internal name; override only the ones you want to rename.
#
# Example: deploy at vc.example.com / auth.example.com / etc., with the
# inji-verify-ui taking the "inji-verify" subdomain (and the backend
# kept docker-internal only):
#
#   VERIFIABLY_SLUG_VERIFIABLY=vc
#   VERIFIABLY_SLUG_KEYCLOAK=auth
#   VERIFIABLY_SLUG_INJI_VERIFY_UI=inji-verify
#   VERIFIABLY_SLUG_INJI_VERIFY=                # backend not exposed
#
# Available slugs: WALT_ISSUER, WALT_WALLET, WALT_VERIFIER,
# INJI_CERTIFY, INJI_CERTIFY_PREAUTH, INJI_VERIFY, INJI_VERIFY_UI,
# INJI_WEB, MIMOTO, ESIGNET, KEYCLOAK, WSO2, VERIFIABLY.
# VERIFIABLY_SLUG_VERIFIABLY=
# VERIFIABLY_SLUG_KEYCLOAK=
# VERIFIABLY_SLUG_INJI_VERIFY_UI=

# -------- External Keycloak (when you don't host your own) ------------------
#
# When VERIFIABLY_KEYCLOAK_EXTERNAL_ISSUER_URL is set, deploy.sh:
#   - skips bringing up a local keycloak container
#   - skips the Caddy route for the keycloak subdomain
#   - skips bootstrap-keycloak.sh (we don't have admin creds)
#   - writes the external URL + client into auth-providers.json so the
#     "Keycloak" tile on /auth uses your existing external Keycloak realm
#
# The realm path is part of the URL — paste the full discovery base
# (e.g. https://auth.example.com/realms/my-realm), NOT just the host.
# Make sure your external Keycloak's client allow-list already contains:
#     https://<your-verifiably-subdomain>/auth/callback
# Since the local bootstrap can't reach the external admin API, this
# allow-list entry has to exist already (added by whoever owns the
# external IdP) before sign-in will work.
# VERIFIABLY_KEYCLOAK_EXTERNAL_ISSUER_URL=https://auth.example.com/realms/my-realm
# VERIFIABLY_KEYCLOAK_EXTERNAL_CLIENT_ID=my-client
# VERIFIABLY_KEYCLOAK_EXTERNAL_CLIENT_SECRET=               # optional for public clients

# =============================================================================
# 2. verifiably-go itself
# =============================================================================
VERIFIABLY_HOST_PORT=8080
VERIFIABLY_ADDR=:8080
VERIFIABLY_IMAGE=verifiably-go:local
VERIFIABLY_CONTAINER=verifiably-go
VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_URL=http://${VERIFIABLY_PUBLIC_HOST}:${VERIFIABLY_HOST_PORT}
# Set to 1 to surface [mock] pills on UI surfaces still backed by mock data.
VERIFIABLY_DEBUG_MOCK_MARKERS=0
# Comma-separated kids to pre-seed into the inji-proxy did.json handler,
# for restarts before any VC has been issued. Usually left empty; the
# proxy self-seeds by watching issued VCs.
VERIFIABLY_INJI_EXTRA_KIDS=

# =============================================================================
# 3. Ports (browser-facing, mapped on the host)
# =============================================================================
# walt.id Community Stack
WALTID_ISSUER_PORT=7002
WALTID_WALLET_PORT=7001
WALTID_VERIFIER_PORT=7003

# Inji Certify (nginx in front of inji-certify:8090)
CERTIFY_NGINX_PORT=8091
# Inji Certify Preauth (separate inji-certify instance for the pre-auth stanza)
CERTIFY_PREAUTH_PORT=8094

# Inji Verify
INJI_VERIFY_UI_PORT=3001
INJI_VERIFY_SERVICE_PORT=8082

# Inji Web wallet + Mimoto BFF + eSignet + mock-identity
INJIWEB_UI_PUBLIC_PORT=3004
ESIGNET_PUBLIC_PORT=3005
MIMOTO_PORT=8099

# Identity providers
KEYCLOAK_PORT=8180
KEYCLOAK_REALM=vcplatform
KEYCLOAK_CLIENT_ID=vcplatform
KEYCLOAK_ADMIN_USER=admin
KEYCLOAK_ADMIN_PASSWORD=admin

WSO2_PORT=9443
WSO2_CLIENT_ID=verifiably_go_client
# WSO2_CLIENT_SECRET is populated by scripts/bootstrap-wso2is.sh on first
# `deploy.sh up`; leave this blank to let the bootstrap generate it.
WSO2_CLIENT_SECRET=

# -------- Pointing OIDC at a different server (single-line update) ---------
#
# verifiably-go's auth registry has three layered config sources, in
# precedence order. Use whichever fits the job:
#
#   1. VERIFIABLY_OIDC_PROVIDERS — JSON array. Replaces config/auth-providers.json
#      entirely. Single env var, single line — best for "swap the whole IdP
#      stack" without touching any file. Example:
#
#         VERIFIABLY_OIDC_PROVIDERS='[{"id":"my_idp","type":"oidc","displayName":"My IdP","issuerUrl":"https://idp.example.com","clientId":"foo","clientSecret":"bar","scopes":["openid","profile","email"]}]'
#
#   2. config/auth-providers.json — file written by deploy.sh's
#      auth_providers_for(). The default for the demo stack (Keycloak +
#      WSO2). Override the path with VERIFIABLY_AUTH_PROVIDERS_FILE.
#
#   3. Per-field scalars — layer on top of (1) or (2) so you only set what
#      changed. ID becomes UPPER_SNAKE in the env-name (id "my-idp" →
#      VERIFIABLY_OIDC_MY_IDP_*). Recognised fields:
#         _ISSUER_URL          _PUBLIC_ISSUER_URL    _CLIENT_ID
#         _CLIENT_SECRET       _DISPLAY_NAME         _KIND
#         _SCOPES (comma)      _INSECURE_SKIP_VERIFY (0/1)
#
#      Example — point the existing keycloak provider at a different server:
#         VERIFIABLY_OIDC_KEYCLOAK_ISSUER_URL=https://idp.example.com/realms/foo
#         VERIFIABLY_OIDC_KEYCLOAK_CLIENT_SECRET=your-secret
#
# All three are optional. Leave them unset to use the demo Keycloak + WSO2
# pair deploy.sh writes.
# VERIFIABLY_OIDC_PROVIDERS=
# VERIFIABLY_OIDC_KEYCLOAK_ISSUER_URL=
# VERIFIABLY_OIDC_KEYCLOAK_CLIENT_SECRET=

# -------- Admin · OIDC providers ----------------------------------------
#
# Surface control for the admin layer that manages OIDC providers.
# Persistence is independent of this flag — providers added via the
# /auth sign-in page always persist to config/auth-providers.user.json
# regardless of mode.
#
#   rw  (default) — full surface: login + list + delete on
#                   /admin/auth-providers, AND the "+ Add OIDC provider"
#                   form on /auth.
#   ro            — admin curates: login + list + delete still work, but
#                   the "+ Add OIDC provider" form on /auth is hidden so
#                   end users can only pick from already-registered tiles.
#   off           — no UI for provider management at all. /admin/* routes
#                   404, "Admin" link hidden, AND the "+ Add" form on
#                   /auth is hidden too. Providers come only from
#                   VERIFIABLY_OIDC_PROVIDERS / auth-providers.system.json
#                   / per-field env overrides.
# Fresh-install bypass: a registry with zero providers always shows the
# bootstrap form on /auth so a single env flag can't lock you out.
VERIFIABLY_AUTH_ADMIN=ro

# Standalone admin credentials. Single shared account, no self-registration.
# Defaults to admin / admin if both are empty. ROTATE BEFORE NON-DEMO USE.
VERIFIABLY_ADMIN_USER=
VERIFIABLY_ADMIN_PASSWORD=

# Skip the demo Keycloak + WSO2 IS bootstrap providers entirely. When set
# to 1, deploy.sh writes an empty auth-providers.system.json and the next
# visit to /auth shows a first-run setup form so the operator can register
# their own OIDC server before any tiles exist. Read by deploy.sh on the
# host — does NOT need to be passed to the container.
# VERIFIABLY_NO_DEFAULT_IDPS=1

# Path to the custom-schemas mirror file. The Registry replays this on
# startup to repopulate per-schema metadata (Custom flag, OwnerKey,
# IssuerDisplayName, DPGs) that walt.id's HOCON catalog can't carry.
# Override only if your container deployment can't write to the
# default path.
# VERIFIABLY_CUSTOM_SCHEMAS_FILE=config/custom-schemas.user.json

# LibreTranslate (app-wide i18n)
LIBRETRANSLATE_PORT=5000

# =============================================================================
# 4. Inji Web / Mimoto secrets
# =============================================================================
# PKCS12 password for wallet-demo-client — must match the p12 in
# deploy/compose/injiweb/config/certs/oidckeystore.p12.
INJIWEB_P12_PASSWORD=xy4gh6swa2i

# Dummy Google OAuth creds for Mimoto's wallet-backup-to-Drive feature.
# Real deployments supply their own; demo deployments keep the dummies.
GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=dummy-client-id
GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET=dummy-client-secret

# =============================================================================
# 5. Postgres (shared container used by walt.id)
# =============================================================================
POSTGRES_USER=waltid
POSTGRES_PASSWORD=waltid
POSTGRES_DB=waltid
POSTGRES_PORT=5432

# =============================================================================
# 6. Walt.id wallet crypto + auth (Phase 1.2 + 7.1)
# =============================================================================
# Defaults below mirror the upstream walt.id demo so a fresh checkout
# behaves identically to before. ROTATE THESE before any non-demo deploy.
# Phase 7.1 replaces this with Vault-backed secrets.
#
# 16 ASCII chars = 128 bits each.
WALLET_ENCRYPTION_KEY=dncygwnvivxzlohc
WALLET_SIGN_KEY=jyjeylmidlylokzh
WALLET_TOKEN_LIFETIME_DAYS=30

# Wallet OIDC login (OFF by default — see deploy/k8s/config/wallet/logins.conf).
# Switching it on requires:
#   1. populating these vars with real values from your IdP
#   2. re-adding "oidc" to enabledLoginMethods in logins.conf
WALLET_OIDC_PUBLIC_BASE_URL=http://localhost:7101
WALLET_OIDC_PROVIDER_NAME=keycloak
WALLET_OIDC_REALM_URL=http://keycloak:8180/realms/vcplatform
WALLET_OIDC_CLIENT_ID=waltid_backend
WALLET_OIDC_CLIENT_SECRET=disabled

# Trust registry — feature stays dormant when these are empty.
WALLET_TRUST_ISSUERS_BASE_URL=
WALLET_TRUST_ISSUERS_TRUST_PATH=
WALLET_TRUST_ISSUERS_GOVERNANCE_PATH=
WALLET_TRUST_VERIFIERS_BASE_URL=
WALLET_TRUST_VERIFIERS_TRUST_PATH=
WALLET_TRUST_VERIFIERS_GOVERNANCE_PATH=
VERIFIABLY_ROLES=issuer,verifier,schemas

# --- Inji auth-code subject provisioning (Flow A) -------------------------
# POST /api/v1/subjects (API-key auth) upserts dynamic claims into Inji
# Certify's certify.vc_subject, keyed by the eSignet PSU-token it computes
# from individualId + the auth-code client. Requires VERIFIABLY_API_KEYS.
# INJI_CERTIFY_DATABASE_URL defaults (inji/all scenario) to certify-postgres;
# unset disables the endpoint (503).
#INJI_CERTIFY_DATABASE_URL=postgres://postgres:postgres@certify-postgres:5432/inji_certify?sslmode=disable
#VERIFIABLY_AUTHCODE_CLIENT_ID=wallet-demo-client

# Optional: authoritative registries the issuer provisioning form can pre-fill from.
# JSON array of {id,label,url,path}; unset = the pre-fill UI is hidden. verifiably stays
# generic -- the specific registries are deployment config, not product code. Example:
# VERIFIABLY_REGISTRIES='[{"id": "dad", "label": "DAD Cultivators (national ID)", "url": "http://dad-registry:8000", "path": "/cultivators/"}]'

# --- Holder activation email (OTP) ---
# SMTP submission for the holder-activation one-time code (/holder/register). When
# SMTP_HOST/SMTP_USER/SMTP_PASSWORD are all set the registry-gated activation flow
# emails a verification code to the address on file in the identity registry; unset
# = email disabled and activation refuses with a clear message. Gmail example
# (use an App Password, NOT the account password):
#   SMTP_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
#   SMTP_PORT=587
#   SMTP_USER=you@gmail.com
#   SMTP_PASSWORD=xxxx xxxx xxxx xxxx   # Gmail App Password — keep out of git
#   SMTP_FROM=you@gmail.com             # defaults to SMTP_USER
#   SMTP_FROM_NAME=Verifiably           # From display name; defaults to "Verifiably"
# The registrar enrols citizen identities (the activation gate) at /registrar/identities
# (admin-gated): plug in a CSV / API / DB / Sunbird RC source and map columns to the
# identity fields. Holders then ACTIVATE — they cannot self-create an identity.
